009package imagingbook.common.color.cie;
010
011import java.awt.geom.Path2D;
012
013/**
014 * This class renders the famous CIE xy-chromaticity diagram, also known as the "horeseshoe" curve, delineating the
015 * range of visible colors in the xy-diagram. The shape is created in a square canvas whose size can be specified.
016 * The result is "upside down", i.e., the vertical coordinate runs from top to bottom.
017 */
018public class CieXyPlot extends Path2D.Double {
019
020    private final double canvasSize;
021
022    /**
023     * Constructor, creates a xy-diagram in a canvas with the specified size.
024     * @param CanvasSize the size of the canvas
025     */
026    public CieXyPlot(double CanvasSize) {
027        this.canvasSize = CanvasSize;
028        this.drawSelf();
029    }
030
031    private void drawSelf() {
032        double[][] coords = CIE1964xyz;
033        for (int i = 0; i < coords.length; i++) {
034            double[] entry = coords[i];
035            // double lambda = entry[0];
036            double X = entry[1];
037            double Y = entry[2];
038            double Z = entry[3];
039            double[] XYZ = {X, Y, Z};
040            double[] xy = CieUtils.XYZToxy(XYZ);
041            double xx = xy[0] * canvasSize;
042            double yy = (1 - xy[1]) * canvasSize;
043            if (i == 0) {
044                this.moveTo(xx, yy);
045            }
046            else {
047                this.lineTo(xx, yy);
048            }
049        }
050        this.closePath();
051    }
052

057     * is truncated above 720nm, thereby skipping the "dangling" measurements.
